=========================================================
OBJECT SLICING IN C++ (INTERVIEW NOTES)
=========================================================

Definition:
Object Slicing occurs when a Derived class object is assigned to a Base
class object by value. The Derived-specific members are "sliced off",
and only the Base part of the object is copied.

=========================================================
WHY IS IT CALLED OBJECT SLICING?
=========================================================

Derived Object:

---------------------------------
Base Part
---------------------------------
Derived Part
---------------------------------

When assigned to a Base object:

---------------------------------
Base Part
---------------------------------

Derived Part is discarded (sliced off).

=========================================================
EXAMPLE
=========================================================

class Base
{
public:
    int x = 10;
};

class Derived : public Base
{
public:
    int y = 20;
};

int main()
{
    Derived d;

    Base b = d;

    cout << b.x;   // 10
    // cout << b.y; // ERROR
}

Output:
10

Reason:
Only Base subobject is copied.

Derived member y is sliced off.

=========================================================
MEMORY REPRESENTATION
=========================================================

Derived Object:

---------------------------------
Base Part
    x = 10
---------------------------------
Derived Part
    y = 20
---------------------------------

After:

Base b = d;

Base Object:

---------------------------------
Base Part
    x = 10
---------------------------------

Derived Part discarded.

=========================================================
ANOTHER EXAMPLE
=========================================================

class Base
{
public:
    int x = 10;
};

class Derived : public Base
{
public:
    int y = 20;
};

int main()
{
    Derived d;

    Base b = d;

